<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="44.[189,310,403,429]" box="[189,310,403,429]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,403,429]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,403,429]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[189,1399,450,687]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
The female of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kuhlmann, 2014" authorityName="Kuhlmann" authorityYear="2014" box="[358,500,450,476]" class="Insecta" family="Colletidae" genus="Scrapter" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="punctatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[358,500,450,476]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">S. punctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[506,596,450,476]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
can be separated from other species of this group by the combination of the following characters: supraclypeal area and clypeus densely and distinctly punctate, shiny, only partly superficially sculptured (
<figureCitation box="[630,740,520,546]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="45.[189,232,1964,1990]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,591,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[189,1399,590,1923]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Fig. 23. Scrapter punctatus sp. nov., ♀. A. Lateral view. B. Head (SEM). C. Thorax (dorsal view). D. Thorax (dorsal view, SEM). E. Metasoma (dorsal view). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860642" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860642/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 23B</figureCitation>
), scutum densely and coarsely punctate, basal area of propodeum medially only slightly longer than metanotum (
<figureCitation box="[886,970,555,581]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="45.[189,232,1964,1990]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,591,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[189,1399,590,1923]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Fig. 23. Scrapter punctatus sp. nov., ♀. A. Lateral view. B. Head (SEM). C. Thorax (dorsal view). D. Thorax (dorsal view, SEM). E. Metasoma (dorsal view). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860642" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860642/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
C–D), stigma brown, apical margins of metasomal terga partly and narrowly brownish translucent, terga densely and coarsely punctate (
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="45.[189,232,1964,1990]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,591,1922]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[189,1399,590,1923]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Fig. 23. Scrapter punctatus sp. nov., ♀. A. Lateral view. B. Head (SEM). C. Thorax (dorsal view). D. Thorax (dorsal view, SEM). E. Metasoma (dorsal view). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860642" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860642/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 23E</figureCitation>
). The male can be separated from all other species of this group by its very long antenna with the last flagellar segment being about as twice as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[889,996,661,687]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="46.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[189,1399,553,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@46.[189,1399,552,1887]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Fig. 24. Scrapter punctatus sp. nov., ♂. A. Lateral view. B. Genitalia (dorsal view, SEM). C. Metasoma (dorsal view). D. S7 (dorsal view, SEM). E. Antenna. F. S8, apical end (SEM). Scale bars: photos: 1 mm, SEM: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3860644" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3860644/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Fig. 24E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
